Taiwan Stocks: AU, Kinsus, Macronix, MediaTek, Nan Kang Rubber

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-07-28T06:18:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-28/au-optronics-mediatek-siliconware-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Taiwan trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 1:30 p.m. close in Taipei.  The Taiex Index fell 50.29 points, or 0.6 percent, to
8,767.20.  AU Optronics Corp. (2409)  (2409 TT) dropped 5.9 percent to
NT$16.70, the biggest loss since March 2, 2009. Taiwan’s second-
largest maker of liquid-crystal displays reported a second-
quarter net loss of NT$10.8 billion ($375 million), compared
with a profit of NT$11 billion a year earlier. The average of 17
analyst estimates compiled by Bloomberg was for a loss of NT$4.5
billion.  Kinsus Interconnect Technology Corp. (3189)  (3189 TT) retreated
4.7 percent to NT$123. The maker of chips for smartphones was
cut to “hold” from “buy” at Citigroup Inc, and lowered to
“neutral” from “outperform” at Credit Suisse Group AG.  Macronix International (2337)  Co. (2337 TT) slid by the 6.9
percent daily limit to NT$15.45, the lowest close since Aug. 27,
2009. The maker of flash-memory chips reported yesterday second-
quarter net income declined to NT$515 million, from NT$2.3
billion a year earlier.  MediaTek Inc. (2454)  (2454 TT) decreased 4 percent to NT$266, the
lowest close since July 19. The chip designer posted second-
quarter net income of NT$3.3 billion, compared with NT$9 billion
a year ago, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Nan Kang Rubber Tire Co. (2101 TT), a tiremaker, surged 6.9
percent to a record NT$58.70, after the Commercial Times
reported that sales at the company’s land development in the Nan
Kang district of Taipei may be more than NT$100 billion ($3.5
billion), citing Jaysanlyn Group’s Chairman Chu Wen-yu. Kuo Mei
Hang, a company spokeswoman, said they have yet to get a
construction license and have no sales estimates. Jasanlyn is
the sales agent for Nan Kang Rubber.  Siliconware Precision Industries Co. (2325)  Co. (2325 TT) fell 1.8
percent to NT$29.70. The chip packaging and testing company said
second-quarter net income was NT$1.1 billion, compared with
NT$1.5 billion a year earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Weiyi Lim in Singapore at 
 wlim26@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
